        <abstract>
            <p>CD’s divergent series explains those anomalous plants that hover between what would otherwise be two species in a genus.</p>
            <p>Inclined to see conifers as a sub-series of dicotyledons that developed in parallel to monocotyledons, but retained cryptogamic characters.</p>
            <p>Mentions H. C. Watson’s view of variations.</p>
            <p>Man has destroyed more species than he has created varieties.</p>
            <p>Variations are centrifugal because the chances are a million to one that identity of form once lost will return.</p>
            <p>In the human race, we find no reversion "that would lead us to confound a man with his ancestors".</p>
        </abstract>
